Primary Land Use: Agricultural with scattered private home development both inland and along the lakeshore.
Live Fish Desc: All observed trout perch were dead or moribund, but otherwise appeared normal.  Both Ryan Koenigs (fisheries LTE) and Doug Rinzel (fisheries tech) noted that many of the trout-perch sampled exhibited "whitish" flesh with in some cases what appeared to be a slight fungus on it, on their sides and/or back near the dorsal fish or on the caudal areas.
Cause Desc: It initially appears that we have had a species-specific die-off of trout-perch due to spawning stresses compounded by a rapid drop in lake temperatures and high winds.  A large sample of fresh dead and moribund fish were tested for VHSv and initial PCR results were negative for it.  No columnaris was detected, but several ubiquitous bacteria were isolated from the kidney, which when fish are stressed can infect the fish and cause mortality.  The stress might have been spawning, but Sue commented that the gills were pale and had hyperplasia (extra cell growth).  Her comment was that if these had been hatchery fish she would have guessed they were on their way toward bacterial gill disease.  She collected tissues for histopathology and has asked the lab to prepare slides.  The time of year/water temps are right about when trout perch spawn.  Water temps had been near 60 degrees, but then have dropped about 10 degrees within a short period following a week of unseasonably cold weather, including nights near or below freezing and sleet/snow showers.  One of Gordy Priegel's articles is referenced in Becker and in it he notes that "in Lake Winnebago, adult trout-perch which have just spawned are washed ashore in great numbers; these are erroneously reported by local residents as a large die-off of small walleyes."  I also mentioned it to Art Techlow (fisheries Biologist) and  he also remembers this happening in the 1960's and 70's, particularly when the trout-perch numbers were high.
Activity Desc: The site is an improved harbor with several boat ramps that are heavily used.  There is overnight docking available.  Mill Creek flow into the harbor at the back end of it.  The creek flows through primarily agriculture and undeveloped land before reaching the harbor.
Fish Kill Comment:
May 14, 2010At approximately 8:30 am on May 14, 2010 I received a phone call from John Nelson, Fisheries Operations Supv. at Asylum Bay who told me that he had been contacted by Warden Mike Disher (Stockbridge) to rely a report of a fish kill on the east shore of Lake Winnebago near Quinney.  Warden Disher was out of the area but was contacted by a Marvin Woelfel (920-439-1624).  Mr. Woelfel resides at N3439 E Winn Rd., Chilton, WI  53014-9483 and had called Warden Disher to report that there were 2 dozen or so 3 - 4' long fish that looked like little walleye.I tracked down and called Mr. Woelfel and talked to him to get further information.  He said that there were 2 or 3 dozen small fish that looked like walleye washed up on the boat ramp at the end of Quinney Road when he was out walking this morning.  I asked if he saw any that were still swimming around but in distress or almost dead and if there was anything on the water like a slick or sheen or any smell.  He said no, that they looked to have been dead a day or two and were likely washed up by the heavy waves and nothing odd about the water.  I asked him if he recalled seeing any dead before today and he stated that he did see a few "floaters" off his dock on Thursday (May 12) but didn't think anything of it.  After talking with Mr. Woelfel, I had fisheries tech Doug Rinzel go to the initial reported site to further investigate and take samples if necessary.  Doug first went to the ramp at Quinney and saw 30 dead fish on 50À of shore at the ramp.  All the fish were adult trout perch.  About a dozen were taken for samples and frozen.  Doug than drove north to Stockbridge harbor to gauge the extent of the die off/kill.  There he observed an estimated 1200 dead fish on roughly 110À of the boat ramp.  In the quieter waters of the harbor he also observed moribund fish.  As at Quinney, the fish were all adult trout perch.  Doug took 30 of the moribund fish for samples.  15 were frozen and 15 were put on ice in the refrigerator over the weekend should Madison want unfrozen samples.  He next  proceeded south to Brothertown harbor.  There he found 100 dead fish on the 50' wide boat ramp.  Again all were adult trout perch.
On his way back to Oshkosh Doug checked Calumet Harbor at Pipe, North Fond du Lac, the wayside on Hwy 45 S, Wendt's and Black Wolf boat landing.  No dead trout perch were seen at any of these sites.
Doug noted that the actual number of dead fish is likely much greater than indicated by the number observed at the 3 locations.  High winds in the previous days, waves in the range of 2.5 - 3 feet, turbid water and the small size of the fish all combined to greatly disperse the dead fish and made them hard to see anywhere except behind sheltered areas.  In addition, the wind and wave action for the last week would disperse most any evidence of a ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION or point discharge. Looking in Becker's "Fishes of Wisconsin" book, this is about the time and temperature that trout perch would start to spawn.  Water temps had been near 60 degrees, but then have dropped about 10 degrees within a short period following a week of unseasonably cold weather, including nights near or below freezing and sleet/snow showers. One of Gordy Priegel's articles is referenced in Becker and in it he notes that "in Lake Winnebago, adult trout-perch which have just spawned are washed ashore in great numbers; these are erroneously reported by local residents as a large die-off of small walleyes." Samples of dead and moribund fish were taken should testing for VHS or other cause be desired.  However, it initially appears that we have had a species-specific die-off of trout-perch due to spawning stress compounded by natural environmental stresses.  The strong winds have concentrated and washed up the stressed or dying/dead post-spawn trout-perch onto areas of the east shore between Brothertown and Stockbridge or possibly further north.  More dead fish may continue to appear

Cause Desc: Thousands of dead fish found in vicinity of Cold Springs boat landing.  Approximately 75% of dead fish were gizzard shad, 20% bluegill, and 5% largemouth bass.  Fish of all sizes were affected.  Large concentration of living fish in poor condition were present near concrete boat launch, many of which were suffering from visible fungal infection.  Dissovled oxygen was measured in the open water near the boat launch and found to be 11.5 mg/l.  Readings taken at ice-covered locations to the north and south were much lower, however, ranging from 0 to 4 mg/l (see Sampling Information).  Earlier conditions of low dissolved oxygen and cold water temperatures may have led to large gizzard shad mortality, with the resulting concentration of dead and dying fish making other species vulnerable to fungal and bacterial infections.0

On June 20, 2011 I received a report of dying fish along the bike path on Lake Monona.  The report stated that there were over 10 bass were discovered.  I investigated the shore line from Olin boat landing to Olbrich boat launch.  The bulk of the fish found were located from the southern John Nolan bridge to the middle John Nolan bridge.  There were carp, all dead at least 3 days.  They numbered less than 20.  Approximately 30 bluegill, 1 Muskie and a couple largemouth bass were also found and had been dead for days.  I saw no evidence of recently dead or distressed fish.  Prior to the report, Lake Monona had been experiencing strong east winds, I believe that these winds piled up the floating fish from the main lake basin. The number of fish found did not seem to be an unusual amount for this lake.

Cause Desc: I investigated the fish kill report for the Yahara river at Lake Monona at 1400 on 3\21\2012.  I found a 12 fresh dead black crappie and 5-6 dead bluegill that had been dead for awhile.  The crappie were vouchered and frozen for later analysis.  Oxygen readings were 157% @ 15.7 mg\l with a water temperature of 55 F.  It seems to be a case of Oxygen super saturation.  Sue will look at the fish and let us know later.

Station Name: ROCK RIVER (HORICON MARSH UPSTREAM) - JOHN DEERE MANUFACTURING PLANT
Location QA Comment: Original Fish Kill Investigation Station, needs review
Cause Desc: John Deere plant's warmwater outfall discharge (70 degrees F) attracted fish.  Unreported water level manipulations (closing the dam) by the USFWS on the north end oJohn Deere plant's warmwater outfall discharge (70 degrees F) attracted fish.  Unreported water level manipulations (closing the dam) by the USFWS on the north end of the Horicon Marsh caused low flow conditions downstream. In response the the upstream dam being closed,  DNR closed the Horicon Dam.   In the absence of upstream dilution, fish appeared to be trapped in the warmwater plume and succumed to thermal stress.
Activity Desc: John Deere manufacturing plant, downtown Horicon businesses, Horicon Marsh located upstream.
Recommended Action Desc: Improved dam operation and communication between USFWS and DNR.  Possible flow gauge installation to monitor river flows so that John Deere can avoid discharging during low flow periods and avoid inducing future fish kills.  John Deere has suggested diverting flow to other outfalls and temporarily diverting cooling water to the sanitary sewer.

Live Fish Desc: Some gulping at surface.
Cause Desc: Hustisford Dam almost completely closed.  Low water and high temps resulted in a D.O. sag combined with temperature shock.
Recommended Action Desc: Better organization and communication between dam operators.  No closing of dams when high air temperatures are forcasted.

Live Fish Desc: lethargic
Cause Desc: High concentrations of fish below the dam, along with a heavy algae bloom and low water caused lethal levels of D.O. (2.0-4.5 mg/L).  High water temps around 27-28 degrees C also contributed.
Fish Kill Comment: D.O. above the dam was also at only 2.2 mg/L and the lake itself was only around 6.0.  Thousands of fish were seen dead.  You could walk across the stream in multiple areas and there were several pools that could trap fish along with a large area of shallow riffle that would have made downstream migration very difficult.

Live Fish Desc: Body condition was good.  No sores, lesions, or redness.  Gills appeared in good overall condition, no clubbing or color change.  Inside of the mouth looked fine.  No gas bubbles seen in or on fish.  Species alive or moribund included bigmouth buffalo, common carp, channel catfish.  Bullheads, blackstripe topminnows, and fathead minnows appeared healthy and alive in decent numbers.
Cause Desc: Low water levels caused fish to be trapped in the plunge pool below the dam.  Water was full of algae and warm (25.5 degrees C).  DO readings were from 3.6-5.5 mg/L.
Fish Kill Comment: Around 1000 bigmouth buffalo, 1000 channel catfish, 500 common carp, and small numbers of bluegill, black crappie, yellow perch, walleye, largemouth bass, pumpkinseed, and black bullhead were found dead on Friday, September 7th.  On Monday, September 10th, only around 200 more bigmouth buffalo were seen dead.  The cool weather and rain over the weekend helped save the remaining live fish.  Many more fish were seen scattering away than on Friday.

Live Fish Desc: Flopping on cobble substrate trying to find water.
Cause Desc: Caused when the upstream Forestville mill pond was drawn down to repair a boat launch at the county park. The increased current flow drew spawning carp to the base of the dam. Recommended Action Desc: Recommend to Door County that if future draw downs are needed that DNR should be informed and flow should be maintained in the Ahnapee River downstream of dam to protect fish.

April 8th a citizen calls in reporting thousands of dead panfish in Cemetery Bay. During June bass anglers report low catch rates and landowners report fishing as slow.

Station Name: KEWAUNEE RIVER AT CLYDES HILL ROAD
Cause Desc: On Monday May 21 it was brought to my attention that a complaint was left on a wildlife answering machine reg. dead crayfish in the Kewanee River. The complaint was left the week of May 14th.  I contacted the complainant (Doug Leinstetter 920-246-9701). The Mr. Leinstetter owns a farm adjacent to the river near Cyde Hill Road.  Mr. Leinstetter stated that his brother witnessed a dead crayfish in the river ~two weeks ago and that he had called the 1-800 number? to report the incident.  I didn't ask what 1-800 service he contacted, the complainant complained that he was unable to contact a warden whereas the 1-800 number would not provide him the cell phone number of a warden. The complainant stated that he was provided with the Mishicot Wildlife Phone number for Kyle Christianson -Wildlife Tech. I contacted Fisheries Biologist, Hogler and Water Quality Biologist, Gansberg both were unaware of a complaint. I traveled to the Kewaunee River on May 21, 2012.  I investigated Cyde Hill Road bridge crossing and obtained access to the Cedar Valley Campground. I did note that dead Crayfish were present. I observed one dead Johnny Darter and a single 9-10 inch brown trout.  I observed living bivalves, small crayfish, numerous stocked rainbow and brown trout (bridge) as well as spawning dace, creek chub and minnow fry at the campground. It was unclear to me if an event occurred. The water appeared cloudy but without sheen normal for the Kewaunee River. The owner of the campground indicated that a flood event did occur ~ two weeks ago. Other, parameters (Temp, DO saturation) were not collected due to a defect with my meter.

Live Fish Desc: Stressed
Cause Desc: Saturday 9/22/2007 5:00pm Dave Vetrano received a call reporting dead fish in Dutch Creek near Bangor in La Crosse County.  Upon investigation, numerous fish were observed dead on the bottom while others were "porpoising".  The water was very dark and foamy.  Residents stated that the creek smelled earlier in the day.  Vetrano investigated further upstream throughout the watershed but could not find an obvious source.  Water appeared to become clearer further upstream.  Sunday 9/23/2007 54 brown trout found dead at Bangor Park, 41 dead (7-18") at Russian Coulee Road, 10 dead (6-10") at Schroeder Road, 4 dead (7-11") at Darling Road, 11 dead (5-15") at Coleman Road, and 32 dead brown trout (4-16") and 1 brook stickleback below the hwy 162 bridge.  Monday 9/24/2007 Fish crew shocked a station at Coleman Road (100m) and found 28 dead brown trout and 9 live trout.  Live trout seemed to be stressed.  There was no evidence that other fish or invertebrate species were affected.  Since, we have found that the kill was originated from a point source in Monroe County (manure-from a facility with 600 head and no storage).  A total of 225 fish were observed dead by fisheries personnel-however we believe that at least 50% of the population died as a result to the manure.  Additional data provided by La Crosse County (guaging station on Dutch Creek) showed a 3 hour period with D.O. at zero on September 22.

Cause Desc: Randy Theobald (sp?) 920-984-3345 called to report dead fish washed up on his Muskellunge Lake frontage.  The fish had sores around their mouths that look "rotten" and one bluegill had a blister-like bubble by the mouth.  He counted 11 dead bluegill and crappie near his dock, over a 20 to 30-foot stretch of shoreline.
Recommended Action Desc: I relayed the report to Lincoln County Fisheries Biologist - Dave Seibel.

Cause Desc: Another angler brought Bob Gilray a sick crappie, about 6 inches TL.  It has red and pink blotches on both sides and was (barely) alive while we were talking.  The blotches extend from the ventral fins to the vent and up along the sides, about the size of a silver dollar.  Bob thought the scales were still intact.  On top of the blotches is a white growth that Bob described as penicillin-like.  The pectoral fin bases are red as well.  I had Bob look at the gills - he described them as a deep violet color, he had not seen gills of that color before.  He did not see clubbing or necrotic tissues.  Bob said he could almost see through the fish - it wasn't clear to me if it was because the fish was so thin or something else.
Recommended Action Desc: I told Bob that this sounds like a fungal or bacterial (columnaris) infection.  The large blotchy redness is not consistent with what I know of VHS.  I talked about Ick and Columnaris and some factors that increase prevalence of Columnaris (spawning, rising temperature, rain that washes nutrients in, gill irritation from pine pollen).  I also told him I didn't think we need to run out there, but to let us know if he sees a large number of dead fish.  The information was passed on to Dave Seibel, Fisheries Biologist for Lincoln County.

Station Name: UNNAMED TRIBUTARY TO DEVILS CREEK US @ ZANDER ROAD
Cause Desc: DATE:        September 27, 2012                FILE REF: [Click here and type file ref.]  TO:        Devils River File  FROM:        Stephen Surendonk  SUBJECT:        Fish Kill Report Unnamed tributary to the Devils River.  -  On September 10, 2012 the Mishicot Fisheries Office (Surendonk) received a complaint (via voice message ~8:15 am) from Fisheries Supervisor Mike Donofrio. Surendonk contacted Donofrio via phone and was advised that Warden Michael Kuhn (Brown County) had responded to a fish kill complain on a unnamed tributary to the Devils River over the weekend. He was requesting support from Department staff for the investigation.  Donofrio stated that the event was documented near the city of Denmark in the stream corridor adjacent to the BelGioioso Cheese Inc. facility on the corner of Highway 96 and Highway NN in Brown County, Wisconsin and at further downstream locations (Figure 1). -  Surendonk contacted Rodney Lange, Fisheries Technician via phone to coordinate a field investigation.  Surendonk requested that Lange bring with him the DepartmentÀs YSI 85 Water Quality Meter and both agreed to meet at the stream crossing on Highway NN at 9:00 am.  -  Surendonk arrived at the Highway NN stream crossing and found that Lange was parked across the street from the BelGioioso Cheese Plant on Hwy NN. Lange was having a conversation with an individual who identified himself as the President of BelGioioso Cheese Incorporated. Surendonk introduced himself as Wisconsin DNR and that he was conducting an investigational response to a reported fish kill in the unnamed tributary. -  The BelGioioso Cheese Inc. President stated he became aware this morning that Department staff had contacted BelGioioso staff over the weekend regarding the fish kill. The individual produced a business card and provided it to Lange. After a short conversation with the BelGioioso representative Surendonk asked permission to enter onto BelGioioso Cheese Inc. property.  This individual responded that we could enter the property and the representative accompanied Lange and Surendonk onto the property (Figure 2).  -  Lange, Surendonk and the BelGioioso representative discussed the unnamed stream at the Highway NN crossing. Surendonk observed that the water was cloudy (white/silver) with a white greasy substance (likely bacteria) covering the channel substrate. Surendonk provided the BelGioioso representative with a sample of the white greasy substance. The BelGioioso representative state if they would have released product it would look different for what Surendonk provided, the BelGioioso representative suggested that we look else were for the source of the event. The BelGioioso representative state that they have "enemies" in the area. - Surendonk stated that the investigation was "just starting".  Surendonk noted a single brook stickleback struggling and tumbling down the channel at this location. Surendonk and Lange measured water quality at Highway NN and found it to contain 1.48 mg/L dissolved oxygen (Table 1). The BelGioioso representative asked what that meant. Surendonk stated that the state standard is 5.00 mg/L dissolved oxygen.  -  Surendonk, Lange and the BelGioioso representative inspected the area near the waste lagoon pit and high content underground holding tanks (HCHT). Surendonk found the area to be unremarkable with the exception of the HCHT that was found to be uncapped (the cement cap was laying in the tall grass and forbs adjacent to the access port). Surendonk did note a small volume of fluid (one square foot) that appeared to coat the upland vegetation between the lagoon and the tributary stream. Surendonk showed the BelGioioso representative the coated vegetation.   The BelGioioso representative stated that one of the "fine" neighbors must have dumped it. -  The BelGioioso representative asked how they could control the "tall grass". Surendonk identified the grass as Phragmites and stated he was unsure, but believed that the plant could be controlled b

Cause Desc: On Monday, November 13, 2006, we received a number of calls from people living on Oneonta Lake, in northern Marinette County,  that fish were dying. The reports indicated that a large number of fish were dead and dying. I along with Tammie Paoli  drove up to Oneonta Lake to investigate. We checked at the access site which is walk in or canoe only down a steep bank. Indeed many, many fish were dead and dying. In an area right in front of the access site about 50' by 25', I counted dead approximately 50 yellow perch, all yoy or yearling size, 6 adult bluegills, 3 Iowa darters, 1 adult rock bass and 1 adult walleye. We then went to one of the lake residents Carl Rodgers, who lives on the east siore of the lake, Lot 25. In front of his dock a similar array of dead fish could be seen, both in number and species. The measurements from the dead fish included in this report came from this site. He then took us in his boat around a short portion of the shore and the picture was the same all over. Dead fish coulsd also be found around the island in the lake. We did not traverse the entire shoreline but dead fish could be found wherever we looked. In the areas I covered I noticed approximately 30 dead adult walleyes. Some live fish could be seen swimming although they had a reduced fright behavior. Time did not allow a complete navigation of the lake shoreline but the kill was very extensive and covered all areas of the shoreline that I saw. Carl Rodgers gave me what I felt was a very accurate timetable of the kill. The y startyed seeing a few fish dying on Friday, November 10, 2006 with increasinmg numbers on Saturday and Sunday. Only limited signs of decopmposition was observed and most of the fish had no visinble appearances that could be tied into the mortality. A few of the crappies had slight hemoraging at the base of the pectoral fins. Fish of all sizes and many different species were observed. Interstingly no northern pike were found dead although they are in the lake. Small yellow perch were the most commonly observed dead fish along the shoreline. As of today, Thursday, November 16, 2006, a few fish are still dying and larger lasrgemouth bass can be seen in the shalow water still showing lethargic behavior. The bass may be the least affect species in regard to actual mortality.
Activity Desc: During the course of the investigation three events surfaced that may or may nor have a bearing on this situation. 1. During the past summer an extensive algae bloom (possibly a diatom bloom) began in late July 2006 and lasted about six weeks until September. The lake resident who told me about it did not recall any such bloom in the past 25 years. It did end and the water cleared by early September. 2. On October 23, 2006, a private fish planting of 300 walleyes and 200 crappies took place on Lake Oneonta. When the fish were stocked about 30 walleyes (6-9") were found dead the next day at the stocking site along with 15 crappies (4-6"). This 10 percent is a releatively high number to die. These dead fish could still be seen with heavy fungus, on the lake botttom, at the stocking site. 3. A fairly heavy snowstorm occurred on November 10, 2006.
Recommended Action Desc: Approximately 15 fish including yellow perch, bluegills, black crappies and rock bass were colloected during the investigation. These fish were all either freshly dead or dying. These fish were kept on ice, refrigerated over night and sent down to Madison the next day, November 14, 2006. Sue Marcquenski wanted these fish for bacterial and/or viral testing. If not to determine the cause perhaps some could be ruled out. Greg Sevener was notified of the incident and get his opinion on possible water quality causes. Numerous lake residents were contacted by Justine Hasz and we are still now in contact with them as they were asked to monitor the situatuiion if things change. In the meantime we will wait on the patholgy testing and if that all proves nwegative we will keep close tabs on potential water quality issues in the future. Oneonta lake appears an unlikely candidate for this type of fish kill. It is a very soft water seepage lake of 66 acres with a maximum depth of 25 feet. It has no history of fish kills. Oneonta Lake has on file an MPA of 4 and a conductance of 32. Electrofish sampling would be very difficult.

Station Name: OAK CREEK US OF 15TH AVE, N OF BEECH ST
Primary Land Use: Mixed urban with small amounts of agricultural row crops in mid- and upper-reaches of watershed
Live Fish Desc: No live fish observed. Rainfall, ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION and high turbidity ~ 12 hrs after reported fish kill made observations difficult to impossible.
Cause Desc: On Thursday, August 16, 2012 at 0830 I responded to a notification of a fish kill along Oak Creek (WIBC 14500), City of South Milwaukee, Milwaukee County. Reported by Mr. Grenier. Following is a summary of my investigation:  I spoke to Mr. Grenier on Thursday morning during my field investigation. According to Mr. Grenier he routinely walks his dog along the same stretch of Oak Creek Parkway every evening, generally between 7 PM and 8 PM, and makes a point to observe the stream. On the evening of Wed., August 15th 1-day prior to his observed fish kill, Mr. Grenier reported nothing unusual; no dead fish, no discoloration, surface material or odors, etc. On the evening of August 16th, he observed between 100 and 200 dead fish from a top of the 16th and Rawson Ave. bridge. He did not observe any discolored water, surface sheens, or odors. He did not recall seeing any stressed or live fish.  On Thursday, August 16, 2012 at 0830 I arrived at the site of the reported fish kill and observed approximately 50 dead fish entangled in overhanging bank vegetation and in other in-stream debris along an ~100-ft reach upstream of 16th Ave. In response to heavy rains that began around 0630 and continued during my investigation, the stream was very turbid with transparency less than a few inches. According to the continuous USGS gage located ~1-mile downstream, Oak Creek flow rose from a base flow of just 3.5 cfs at 0700, to 32 cfs at 0715, to 62 cfs at 0720. A typical response for urbanized watersheds without stormwater abatement.  I proceeded upstream to an additional 4 road xings and 3 park trail access points up to Marshall Ave. extended. I observed a decreasing number of dead fish up to Marshall Avenue extended where I did not observe any dead fish. I canÀt say for certain that this was the furthest upstream extent of the fish kill or source of killing agent as the high stream flows could have removed dead fish from upstream reaches. I did not observe any stressed or live fish due to the high turbidity, dead or stressed invertebrates, or other wildlife at any of the sites. I estimated 200-300 dead fish in the ~500-ft of stream that I walked. ~80% were White suckers of various year classes 3-12 inches; ~15% Creek chubs also of multiple year classes; and <5% as Green sunfish, Central mudminnow, and a single Black bullhead. None of the inspected fish displayed any obvious deformities, eroded fins, lesions, tumors (DELTs), or parasites. This suggests that the killing agent was not selective among fish species or age-class.  I met with Lieut. Peter Jaske (414) 768-8060 of the South Milwaukee police department and summarized what I observed. He was not aware of the incident and would be contacting other officers and city department heads to get their feedback, and let me know if anything comes of his inquiry. I also contacted Chris Magruder of the Milw. Metro. Sew. District (MMSD) and requested information on precipitation amounts leading up to the fish kill, specifically the 0.8 cfs ÀbumpÀ in the stream flow observed on Wed., Aug. 15th around 1330 (see stream gage plot below). This bump may be associated with a minor and brief precipitation and ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION event, or a point source discharge. A brief malfunction in the gage cannot be discounted. The MMSD routinely collects physical, chemical and biological water quality data at numerous streams and sites as part of their monitoring program, and according to Chris the field crews sampled Oak Creek on Wed. August 15th.  Instantaneous water quality measures using multi-probe sonde, laboratory analysis for conventional pollutants (i.e., nutrients, solids, BOD, etc.) and select heavy metals did not reveal any obvious killing agent or surrogate parameter that may have suggested impacted water quality (i.e., conductivity or turbidity spike).
Activity Desc: Road constructioon ~ 2 miles upstream of impacted reach
Recommended Action Desc: Complete synoptic field assessment for fish and macroinvertebrates
Fish Kill Comment: I did not observe any stressed or live fish due to the high turbidity, dead or stressed invertebrates, or other wildlife at any of the sites. I estimated 200-300 dead fish in the ~500-ft of stream that I walked. ~80% were White suckers of various year classes 3-12 inches; ~15% Creek chubs also of multiple year classes; and <5% as Green sunfish, Central mudminnow, and a single Black bullhead. None of the inspected fish displayed any obvious deformities, eroded fins, lesions, tumors (DELTs), or parasites. This suggests that the killing agent was not selective among fish species or age-class.

Cause Desc: Possible delayed mortality from walleye tournament held on 8/12/07 (see below). This was to be a live-release tournament, with all fish to be returned to Green Bay waters after registration. Oconto Sportsman's Club to provide release pontoon boat.
Activity Desc: Fishing tournament "Battle on the Bay" held on August 12, 2007 and sponsored by Sheboygan Walleye Club.  Waterbody of fishing tournament: Green Bay. Weigh-in site: Oconto Breakwater Boat Ramp. Greater than 20 boats estimated.
Recommended Action Desc: On 08/14/07 at about 10:30 am Warden Stahl received a call from a male fisherman who seemed very upset about a number of large walleyes that were dead in the area of the Oconto Breakwater Boat Ramp. Subject felt that there were about 25 large walleyes and he was blaming the deaths on the recent walleye fishing tournament that had taken place at Oconto on 08/12/07. Warden Stahl informed the suspect that he would pass the information onto fisheries to investigate. Warden Stahl contacted Peshtigo DNR and found that all fisheries staff was out in the field. Warden Stahl then contacted fish biologist Tammie Paoli and she said she was currently out on the trawler in the southern bay. She asked if Warden Stahl could verify the fish kill and pick up the fish in question. Warden Stahl said that he would look into it. Warden Stahl did respond to Oconto and picked up the Oconto Boat and put in at City Docks. Warden Stahl then motored downstream and did find one large walleye dead against the start of the south break wall. Warden Stahl continued out to the end of the south break wall and then came back along the north break wall. One large walleye was located along the north break wall bayside of the jetty. Warden Stahl found most of the fish (25) in site of the boat landing with 12 large fish on the boat landing apron. Warden Stahl had been in the area the night before and only observed one fish on the apron. The fish were starting to decay but were intact other than some sea gull damage. The fish ranged from 18" to 31" with most being well over 20". Warden Stahl did find one more fish in the turn around basin just upstream from the boat landing. A total of 28 large walleyes were retrieved. No other dead fish were observed other than 2 badly decomposed sheephead. Warden Stahl did take several photos of the fish.  On 8/17/07, Tammie Paoli spoke to a contact (Patrick Schuette) with the Sheboygan Walleye Club to clarify how the tournament was run. He had heard that there were some dead fish but didn't realize to what extent. He said that they did end up sacrificing quite a few fish that didn't look like they had a chance of survival, and only released those fish that they felt looked "good". Therefore he was quite surprised to hear that there were 28 dead fish washed up on shore.   We discussed some actions that could have helped prevent the fish kill. The release pontoon boat released the fish just upstream from the boat landing rather than in the bay. This was due to the length of time it took to shuttle fish from the landing back out to the bay, and stronger east winds would not allow the pontoon boat to get out far. He said that water temperatures in the river were similar to the surface temps in the bay, so the event organizers felt that releasing the fish in the river would give them a good chance of survival.   Other actions that his club is considering in future tournaments is a smaller (2 or 3 fish) limit to reduce crowding in livewells, and a stiffer weight penalty for bringing in fish that are dead or nearly dead. Pat will be sending the summary of the tournament (page 2 of the permit application) to Tammie Paoli. This fish kill information was forwarded to Andy Fayram, the contact for WDNR tournaments.

Live Fish Desc: By monday afternoon all fish were quite decomposed and no freshly dead or moribund fish were present.  All dead fish observed were 5-7 inch black crappies except for a couple of bluegills as well.   When CO Stahl was present Sunday morning there were some freshly dead and he collected four for examination.  Upon investigating the littoral margin of the lake on Monday afternoon live fish appeared to be behaving normally; northern pike, largemouth bass, bluegill, yellow perch, unidentified cyprinids were all observed and looked and behaved normal.
Cause Desc: Heavy growth of filamentous algae decomposing combined with warm temperatures lead to local pockets of reduced O2 and lead to columnaris outbreak.   This lake is small with very tannin stained water.  The secchi depth was only 4.5 feet, and the thermocline was at 6 feet.  The hypolimnion was anoxic.  Surface temperature was 82 degrees F.  The littoral margin also has heavy submergent and emergent plant growth.  Heavy rainfall has likely increased the nutrient load fueling algal growth.  Some blue green cyanobacteria was seen but not a lot (CO Stahl did not observe bg algae on Sunday).  CO Stahl first recieved a complaint on Saturday and likely the fish kill happened on Friday evening/Saturday morning.

Cause Desc: Recent, heavy rainfall.  Columanris suspected but fish to degraded for analysis.  Water samples collected for algal counts and NH3 analysis.

Sue Marcquenski (Fish Health Specialist) examined collected fish and concluded: "I did not take any cultures from the fish since there were no signs of a contagious disease- my conclusion is the fish were exposed to poor water quality for an extended period and died from suffocation (not enough O2 could transfer across the gills due to the severe hyperplasia (clubbing))." My hypothesis: It is possible that a diatom bloom was a factor (gill irritation).

Cause Desc: On June 7, an angler delivered a 10-inch,  live rock bass to the Rhinelander Service Center.  He had caught the fish (hook and line) on 06 June 2007 and kept it alive in his livewell; he delivered it wrapped in a plastic bag and placed in a cooler.  No other impaired fish were observed.  The fish had faint red areas in several (~3) 1-2 inch patches on its skin that looked like a scrape or a light rash, making him concerned about VHS.  The slime layer appeared to be missing in those areas; scales were intact.  The patches were scattered, not paired like bite marks from another fish, but could have been abraisions from a rough surface.  The fish also had a faint yellowish area on its skin that looked like an infection on the skin surface which had displaced the normal slime layer.   The most distinct yellowish patch was on the belly covering about 1 inch of skin from the vent forward, and was about 1/2 inch wide.  The gills appeared normal except they were somewhat frayed, possibly due to handling and being out of the water.  I cut a fillet from the left side of the fish -- the muscle tissue appeared normal.  Internal organs were also normal, with good color.  Overall condition of the fish appeared to be good, except for the skin areas.  I suspect a bacterial infection on the skin surface, possibly Columnaris.

Suspect Columnaris based on timing and extent.

On 6/13, I received a voicemail from Harry Helwig (715-369-2549), President of Julia Lake Association, relaying fish kill reported to him.  On 6/14, talked to Mr. Helwig and a Mrs. Brown on the phone, as well as a lake resident in person (didn't record his name).  Mr. Helwig had collected one bullhead and told me that a kayaker had reported 14 dead perch, bluegill and pumpkinseed and one largemouth bass on Lake Julia on June 13 2007.  The majority of the fish were bluegill and pumpkinseed.  One of Mrs. Brown's sons had counted 34 dead fish (species unknown) on her frontage, west side of the lake, within a 50-foot area.  On June 13, the same son had observed live fish swimming on their sides and "missing their skin."  Another son had told her 7 species were dead in his bay "last week".  Mrs. Brown did not recall all the species, but they included bluegill, rock bass, black crappie and white sucker, but no game species.  All the dead fish were "little bitty fish", 2-4 inches TL.  She also reported that there were a number of very stinky dead fish around Nicolet College on the east side of the lake and she believed some of these had drifted to her shore.  A third individual visited the Rhinelander Service Center on 6/14 to report a fish kill that had been occurring "from the middle of last week to this week."  He reported bullhead (6-8"), largemouth bass (8-12"), black crappie (4-8"), 'sunfish' (4-6"), bluegill (4-6") and a couple small northern pike.  Bullhead and bass were the most numerous.

Theresa Gauthier (715-369-1690) left a voicemail reporting dead fish on her frontage on the north side of Thompson Lake.  Each of the last few days, she has had 6-7 dead fish on her 150 feet of frontage.  She also noted 'suds' on the shore, but only in the mornings.  She described the fish as "normal" in appearance, except for bloating (because they are dead).  I called and left a voicemail on June 6, describing the characteristics of Columnaris-related fish kills that I typically observe in the area around this time of year.  I instructed her to call me back if it seems to be something different or if she has additional concerns.

Dennis Wittig (715-362-3666) called, then brought in 2 frozen walleyes that lake residents had brought to him.  1.  15.0 inch angler-caught walleye with a red, raised, blister-like lesion on its skin, about the size of a pencil eraser.  The lesion was on the left side, halfway back on the body, 1 inch below the lateral line.  On the right side of the body just above the belly, the skin had a faint red-pink patch of color, 2-inch long, 3/8" wide.  Internal tissues unremarkable.  2.  12.8 inch walleye floated up dead on the beach at South Bay campground.  Gills pink-gray, starting to soften and slight rotton odor.  The only noticeable mark was a 1 inch diameter circular scrape-like mark on the right side, centered on the lateral line, and beneath the junction of spinous and soft dorsal fins.  The mark had scales mostly intact, but some were raised and the skin roughened.  It was covered with an opaque slime that looked like a bacterial or fungal infection.  I did not cut into the fish.  3.  Dennis described seeing a gamefish (he thought bass or walleye) in shallow water, swimming rapidly in circles and "going berserk".  The fish did this for a short time, then left the area.  Dennis was concerned because he had heard disoriented swimming and spinning is a symptom of VHS.  (?)  There was a small panfish kill consistent with Columnaris reported from Thompson on 6/6/2007.  Skin infections on the 2 fish may be additional Columnaris type infections.  Fish swimming in circles has a variety of possible causes, including a healthy fish swimming in circles, predator chasing prey, or stressed by injury or disease.
Recommended Action Desc: I gave Dennis another handout on VHS and we talked about the appearance I would expect to see in a VHS-infected fish versus a fish with a surface infection of the skin caused by something other than VHS.

Cause Desc: Rose Scheibe (715-356-1186) called to report 2 dead bass.  The first bass (smallmouth) was about 14 inches long.  She found it dead, floating head-down on Sat., 5/26/2007.  It appeared to be just fine, except it "looked like it had this hemorrhagic septicemia eye."  The eye was red and blood-shot.  On Wed., 5/30/2007 she found a dead largemouth bass, much larger than the smallmouth.  Rose said "its eye was not as red as the first fish."  She described one gill as somewhat mangled, and we agreed that this fish may have died from a hooking injury.  We discussed the symptoms on the phone and determined that it is not necessary for me to examine the fish.

Sandy Wickman (Water Resources Mgmt. Specialist) visited Manson Lake on June 11 to collect plant samples.  She observed moderate numbers of decomposing bluegills and rock bass  near the boat landing and around lake -- about 30 by landing.  Sandy did not see "blood lines" (she was looking for symptoms of VHS).  Most of the fish were "smaller."

Primary Land Use: Lakefront residential with some areas of natural shore.
Fish Kill Comment: Timing, fish species and size consistent with Columnaris; no fresh fish to verify with.

Cause Desc: Suspect Columnaris based on timing and species.

Primary Land Use: Northern lake with moderate development, extensive bog wetlands.
Live Fish Desc: none observed
Cause Desc: Dead fish noticed just before ice-out - lake still mostly ice-covered.  Fish were scattered along a 30 to 40 foot stretch of shoreline in 2 feet of open water.  I did not make a site visit.
Fish Kill Comment: Fish kill reported by riparian owner Susan Watson.   Described fish 3-5" total length, golden in color, charcoal dorsal fin, flat-sided.  Sound like golden shiner.  Susan noted last winterkill was 1989 (bass).

Primary Land Use: NHAL State Forest.  Cross country ski trail skirts portions of the shoreline.
Cause Desc: Skier (Robin Stafford, Rhinelander) noted "a mess of dead bass in the outlet on the north end of the lake."  McNaughton experiences frequent winterkills.

Live Fish Desc: Unknown
Cause Desc: Timing and species suggest columnaris.
Fish Kill Comment: Called in on 6/23 to Vincent Scipior, Chemical ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION reporting hotline; relayed via e-mail.

Lake Association contact reported a moderate-sounding panfish winterkill to Lake Planning consultant Eddie Heath, who passed it on to me.  No direct report or details received.  Mid Lake has a history of winterkill.

Cause Desc: Symptoms and timing consistent with Columnaris, but riparian also reported unauthorized chemical treatment for aquatic plants.
Activity Desc: Unconfirmed report of chemicals used on aquatic plants.
Recommended Action Desc: Warden Tim Ebert investigated the rumor of chemical use but could not find the original source of the complaint.  No further action taken.

Cause Desc: Steve Ave'Lallemant (Northern Region Fisheries Supervisor) said "I heard there were some dead fish on Minocqua too."  Earlier in the week, someone in the office mentioned in passing that their daughter told them there were a number of stinky dead fish in the slips near the Thirsty Whale - they were unsure of species or specific numbers.  Thirsty Whale is located in the shallower west basin of the lake.
There was some suspician by riparians that chemical treatment for Eurasian water milfoil on June 05-06 contributed to the kill.
Noted 3-4 dozen panfish that had been dead several days.  Found 1 fresh bluegill.  Steve Gilbert examined and noted symptoms of Columnaris infection.
Fish Kill Comment: Dead fish were found in a small bay off Brunswick Road.

Recommended Action Desc: None, unless additional fish show signs of disease or a fish kill is observed

Cause Desc: Small to medium size bluegill, black crappie, pumpkinseed.  White film around mouth area.
Fish Kill Comment: Small fish kill, likely Columnaris related.  Further investigation warranted if numbers or species changes dramatically.

Live Fish Desc: None observed
Cause Desc: Dead fish showed up at ice-out.
Fish Kill Comment: Reported by Mrs. Chris Schiek, 715-282-6181.  She first noticed 4/25, but neighbors had mentioned it 4/23.  Counted 20 right by her pier, could see 100 or fewer from the pier.  5-7 inches, unsure of species.

Cause Desc: Nicole Nikolaus (LTE - Water Res. Mgmt. Specialist) reported a moribund smallmouth bass about 15" TL floating near her parents' frontage on Paradise Lake.  Its gills were full of fuzzy-looking material (fungus) and its fins were red and severely eroded.  It was tagged with a yellow floy tag with Gary Yamamoto's website and a C&R message.  Many of the bass in the lake apparently have these tags.  No other sick or dead fish were noted.
Recommended Action Desc: Contact Mr. Yamamoto and tell him to cease illegal fish-tagging activities.  I also offered to write a short paragraph on fish tagging for the Lake Association newsletter.

Cause Desc: Two separate anglers reported catching single northern pike with red sores or lesions on the skin.  No mortality observed beyond the angler-caught fish.  I estimate length of the first fish (5/18/2007) at about 20 inches TL.  It was frozen and delivered to my office on 5/21/2007.  It had 3 red lesions on the sides and belly, each about the size of a nickel.  The angler described the dorsal fin as red and the body as red-tinged or flushed, but this was not apparent on the frozen specimen.  The second fish (caught 5/21/2007) was reported to me by resort owner Jim Sharon by phone (715-487-5473).  It was a 24-inch northern pike that was reported to have a "weird-looking rash all over the body."  The caller was not the angler and had not looked at the fish, which had been wrapped in newspaper and frozen.  From the description, it sounded like it had a similar appearance to the first fish.  Possible Lymphosarcoma.

Live Fish Desc: Live fish infected with fungus were sitting vertically in the water column at rest (head or tail up), but swam off when approached by boat.
Cause Desc: Suspect Columnaris or other bacterial infection with secondary fungal infection.
Recommended Action Desc: Kill seemed to peak over weekend of June 13-14.  I asked several individuals to call me if the situation changed or additional fish were dying.  I also offered to submit fresh fish for testing but only received fish that had been dead for 2 days and were starting to decompose.
Fish Kill Comment: Perch with fungus.  Two observers noted large schools of 3-5 inch perch, with about 10 to 20% of the fish infected with an apparent fungus.  After weekend of June 13-14 I received several reports of moderate numbers of dead, fungused perch on the bottom.

Cause Desc: Suspect Columnaris based on timing and extent.

On 14 June, Kevin Gauthier (Water Resources Mgmt. Specialist) received a phone call from Barb Thompson, 362-5469, regarding dead fish on the shore of Pine Lake near Crosscountry Road.  She reported about 12 dead fish.  Kevin discussed the type of kills typically associated with Columnaris, but also told her a Fisheries Biologist would call her back.  I called her back on 6/15 but was unable to reach her; no answering machine.

Headwaters Fisheries Supervisor Mike Vogelsang received two phone calls on June Headwaters Fisheries Supervisor Mike Vogelsang received two phone calls on June 5 and 6 that sounded like Columnaris-type fish kills on Shishebogama Lake.  The first caller (June 5) reported 8 to 10 dead fish.  The second caller (June 6) reported about 30 dead fish, mostly bluegill and a few black crappie.  They had also collected some live, moribund fish.  Mike went through the list of symptoms for Viral Hemorrhagic Septicemia on the phone, but none of them matched the appearance of the collected fish.  Symptoms were consistent with Columnaris.  Connected Gunlock Lake also had a fish kill reported.

Primary Land Use: Lakeshore residential with some large areas of undeveloped shoreline.
Live Fish Desc: Normal
Cause Desc: No dead fish observed on my 08-July-2008 site visit.
Activity Desc: Jim reported seeing jet skis the day before (06 July 2008) in shallow water and suspected they somehow caused the fish kill.  This is the first time he's seen a fish kill in 50 years on the lake.

Primary Investigator Name:
John Kubisiak
John Kubisiak
John Kubisiak
Cause Desc: A Minocqua resident with a cabin near the Squirrel Lake boat ramp on Bois-Di-Lac Drive called to report a fish kill on 6/21/2006.  Caller described "lots" of small bluegill, fairly decomposed already.  I told her it is most likely Columnaris, but there is no way to be sure with rotten fish.
Recommended Action Desc: Instructed the caller to let me know if they find fresh/stressed fish that I could sample.

Cause Desc: Diana McKee (I am unsure of last name), 630-690-4893; cell 630-272-1010 called to report dead fish on Squirrel Lake.  Over the June 16-17 weekend, she found 60 dead fish on her 396 feet of frontage; there were another 50-60 that washed up on her neighbor's frontage over the last 2 weeks, 40 of these had washed up the weekend of June 9.  The fish were very rotten and Diana buried them.  Primarily bluegill and pumpkinseed (about 6 inches), moderate numbers of yellow perch, a few smalmouth bass and 1 white sucker ~ 12" TL.
Recommended Action Desc: We talked about the characteristics of a Columnaris-type fish kill.  Diana said she had owned the property for 3 years and had never seen a fish kill.  I told her a small fish kill similar to what she was seeing was reported on Squirrel Lake last summer (June 21, 2006).  Wind direction plays a role in the locations where fish wash to shore.  Diana was mainly concerned with human health and whether it is safe for her kids to swim.  I said it would be ill-advised to swim among rotting fish carcasses, but swimming in clear water should be OK.  I also discussed bacterial load in the nearshore water and told her to be careful not to ingest the water.

Cause Desc: Suspect columnaris based on timing and extent.

Greg Walker (General Manager, Lakeland Times in Minocqua) called to report a kill on Stone Lake near his residence.  He estimated 25 to 50 dead fish on 100 yards of frontage -- he was on the windward shore.  Primarily 3-5 inch bluegill, with a few up to 10 inches; a couple 3 inch yellow perch and one black crappie, about 10 inches.

Live Fish Desc: Resident reported one stressed sucker finning near surface.
Cause Desc: Sue Henderson (773-519-1001 cell) visited the Rhinelander Service Center to report dead suckers near her frontage on Sugar Camp Lake.  Her cottage is on the shallow south basin of the lake.  She observed about 15 dead suckers, 10-15 inches in length, along about 300 feet of shoreline over the last 3 days:  about 3 on 8/19; 6 on 8/20 and 6-7 on 8/21.  She also saw 1 large (12-15 inches) dead bullhead last week, in a different location (possibly unrelated).  On 8/22 I had a voicemail from "Peter" (847-946-5346) regarding 20 dead fish on Sugar Camp Lake off Maple Road.  The fish "look like carp" and were scattered between 2 piers.  I called Peter back and left a voicemail reply.
Recommended Action Desc: None unless a more significant kill is reported.
No action recommended for a single yoy fish.  Nothing unusual was observed during spring, 2009 muskellunge recapture survey.
Fish Kill Comment: Angler Craig Kuehl caught a bluegill (misidentified as a smallmouth bass) in the water from drilling an ice hole on December 27; it was still alive when it splashed out of the hole.  The fish has a red blotch, and Craig thought the eyes were too large.  He placed it in a small vial and buried it in a snow bank until Feb. 7, when he dug it out and gave it to DNR creel clerk Bill Brener.  He suspects VHS and told Bill he would like the fish to be tested with information back to him.  Bill took possession of the fish and placed it in another snow bank until he could bring it in to me.  I received the fish on February 9.  The fish was fairly intact, but has a slight odor of decomposition.  I noticed a red blotch on the left side near the vent and the right eye has faint red streaks.

Cause Desc: On 6/8, Robin Stafford sent me an e-mail,  reporting a number of dead bluegill on Wildwood Lake 6/7/2008.  Wildwood is near my residence, so I visited at the end of the day.  I accessed the lake at Rich & Marlene Emiley's property, 4511 Warner Drive.  Rich reported disposing of a couple 'nice-sized' bluegill each day for the last week on his 200 feet of frontage; highest numbers 4 to 5 days ago (June 3-4, 2007).  Almost all were rotten when they washed up.  I observed a rotten yellow bullhead on Mr. Emiley's beach, about 10-12 inches long.  With assistance from Ben and Jane Kubisiak (ages 6 and 8), I boated around the entire lake about 50 feet from shore, but observed only 1 more dead fish (a narrow band of pickerel weed partially obscured much of the shoreline but I would have seen any significant numbers).  Adult and juvenile bluegill were observed near a colony of nests; Ben and Jane captured about a dozen hook-and-line, about 5-6.5 inches TL.  We kept 6 to test edibility; the fillets were lightly peppered with black spot but tasted fine.  The dead fish was a bluegill on the bottom in 2.5 feet of water, 3.4 inches TL, with faded pink gills.  Skin and right gill appeared normal.  About 1/4 of the left gill tissue was missing, with a band of yellow necrotic tissue around the missing chunk.  The gill tissue was a deep red color in a band surrounding the yellow tissue.

Live Fish Desc: Observed live fish were gulping air.
Cause Desc: The lake is drawn down 3' for aquatic plant management.  Last ~3 weeks of hot temperature and little wind or rain activity likely led to warm water temperatures.  Respiration and decomposition of organic material caused an over-night sag in dissolved oxygen leading to a partial summer kill.
Activity Desc: Once again the lake was partially drawn down as part of aquatic plant management program.  Heavy storms prior to event may have increased organic material present in the water resulting in higher BOD.
Recommended Action Desc: No immediate action.  Pending severity, stocking may be recommended.  Fisheries staff will survey lake with fall electro-fishing to compare to previous data.
Fish Kill Comment: 300-500 dead fish observe, in order of numbers: white sucker, bluegill, yellow perch, northern pike, largemouth bass

Location QA Comment: Original Fish Kill Investigation Station, needs review
Cause Desc: COLD SHOCK - Related to cold front moving through the state last week and observed by Kendall Kamke of DNR on other areas of the Fox River with gizzard shad.

Location QA Comment: Original Fish Kill Investigation Station, needs review
Live Fish Desc: Disoriented and with obvious injuries
Cause Desc: Gizzard shad appear to be getting killed when passing through the We Energies hydro plant in Appleton.  Observed many fish with injuries consistent with turbine strike below hydro plant.

Location QA Comment: Original Fish Kill Investigation Station, needs review
Fish Kill Comment: Collected a 35 inch Musky that was on the We Energies intake screen. Fish had red marks along it's sides. Sent to Madison for VHS testing.

Location QA Comment: Original Fish Kill Investigation Station, needs review
Live Fish Desc: Upstream of Hydro units all fish appeared normal.  Downstream of Hydro units only gizzard shad were observed to be moribund and showed evidence of turbine strike injuries.
Cause Desc: Combination of natural temperature fluctuation and entrainment through hydropower turbines at WE energies facilities Appleton, caused death and injury of 10,000 of young of the year gizzard shad.
Fish Kill Comment: 10-100,000 of young of the year gizzard shad were killed or wounded when they passed through the WE energies hydro-turbines.  Likely the recent temperature fluctuations of over 10 degrees farenheit caused the gizzard shad to try and migrate downstream from Little Lake Buttes des Mortes.

Live Fish Desc: Very lethargic swimming on their side with some red scrapes
Cause Desc: Gizzard Shad dying from water temp changes
Fish Kill Comment: Every year we see this happening from the shad being at the northern edge of their range and the water temp fluctuations. Also they are very delicate.

Location QA Comment: Original Fish Kill Investigation Station, needs review
Cause Desc: dead freshwater drum by sewage treatment plant in Menasha reported by Mary Welsh (920 725-0134)

Live Fish Desc: Fish were at the water surface stressed and gasping for air.
Cause Desc: Contruction company drained down a canal to do work on an intake. Fish then were trapped in a pool and eventually a lot died from low oxygen.

Location QA Comment: Original Fish Kill Investigation Station, needs review
Cause Desc: Donald Schinke (715 752-4486) caught 2 freshwater drum both of which exhibited symptoms of VHS (10" and 13"). Indicated that he had caught approximately 100 fish of different species and these were the first with symptoms. Drum in the Winnebago System have already tested positive for VHS so no testing was done.

Primary Land Use: Wolf River Bottoms - relatively pristine riparian
Fish Kill Comment: Citizen called in reports of dead northern pike from STH 45 crossing upstream to CTH M.  20-30 large pike up to 38 inches.   This report goes along with similar reports from downstream areas.

Live Fish Desc: none seen
Cause Desc: suspected winter kill of rough fish caught in river backwaters - no dead fish were found in response to call to DNR hotline of fish kill in area
Activity Desc: message left to hotline caller - no response as of 7days later - report was of numerous dead fish in area - no dead fish found
Fish Kill Comment: I suspect receding high water trapped carp in river backwater during late winter. Fish then winterkilled and were observed by caller. Were likely decomposed or hidden by high water when investigated

Cause Desc: winterkill

Live Fish Desc: No live fish observed. Assume 100% kill of all Centrarchids. Other species not observed in kill. Numerous live Northern leapord frogs observed and appeared healthy. No other impacted fauna observed. Emergent wetland/shoreline vegetation appeared normal. All dead fish in advanced state of decomposition making examination impossible.
Cause Desc: Willowbrook Park Pond, City of Cedarburg, Ozaukee County. Cause of fish kill unknown.  Initially reported by Josh Skarston (414) 588-5257 on Friday, Sept. 20, 2013 at 4:18 PM to Katelyn Johnson, WDNR. Forwarded to Will Wawrzyn DNR FM with cc: to LE Hotline, Tony Young DNR LE and Travis Motl DNR FM. Will Wawrzyn was out of office until Monday morning ~ 11:30 AM, Sept. 23, 2013.  Warden Tony Young was contacted prior to leaving for site and confirmed fish kill. Kill may be a result of dissolved oxygen depletion associated with warm runoff event and nightime/cloudy aquatic plant respiration and decomposition. Pond appears to be hypereutrophic based on extensive coverage by Lemna spp., Elodea spp. and filamentous algae.
Activity Desc: According to Kevin Westphal, C. of Cedarburg Parks Supt. (262) 375-7662 ex. 4), light rain (0.1") was recorded on Sept. 18, 2-days prior to observed fish kill date. More accurate precip measures were obtained from the Cedarburg wasterwater facility. Precip amounts (inches) between Sept 15-20 were:  0.41, 0, 0, 0.15, 0.45 and Trace, respectively. He indicated that the pond received water from a sand and gravel pit NE of the City but that the discharge was absent or much more infrequent during these summer. Walked the entire pond shoreline and observed 2 storm sewers. The largest located on the north side of the pond. A smaller storm inlet located on the south west side of the pond. Neither was observed flowing at time. Some floating debris as plstic wrap and plastic beverage bottles. Lemna spp. covering ~ 30% of surface primarily the eastern 1/3 of surface and wind blown side. Macrophytes dominated by Elodea spp. and covering the entire visable littoral substrate. Filamentous benthic algae Spirogyra spp. also abundant. Water dark, stained black. No odors aside from decomposing fish noted. No surface scums or petroleum-like sheens observed. Small randomly scattered surface sheen associated with breakdown of aquatic plant material (fatty acids) observed throughout pond. Outlet located at south end of pond with ultimate discharge to Cedar Creek. Ponded from recent overflow associated with previous rainfall/ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION event. Bank vegetation matted down from receded high flows along channel. Drainage from Ozaukee County Fair Grounds and detention ponds discharge to outlet tributary and not to the pond. No dead fish located in tributary outlet.
Recommended Action Desc: Have access to calibrated dissolved oxygen/temperature meter. Follow up with City of Cedarburg park staff for interview.
Fish Kill Comment: Estimate approximately 75-100 Bluegill and 25 Largemouth bass, and 3 Green sunfish. initial report estimated 500-600 dead fish as Bluegill and Largemouth bass.

Cause Desc: Severe winter with early ice formation and heavy snow cover. Delayed aeration system start-up due to large amounts of water and slush on the ice.
Fish Kill Comment: Large amounts of gamefish and panfish observed by lake property owners along shoreline at ice-out.

I received a call, from Kris Muller 825-5357 regarding a large amount of dead fish -- mostly black crappies in the vegetation on the west side of East Balsam lake.  They did not observe any dead or dying gamefish. I explained that it sounds like a columnaris outbreak which has been occurring in area lakes. I explained the syptoms and asked them to call back if they start seeing very large amounts of additional fish especially gamefish.
see comment on wapogasset for same dates - same call.

Cause Desc: Water temp mid-upper 60"s.  Report of 100 dead panfish along the shore.  Suspect colmnaris.  No other fish reported dead.
Fish Kill Comment: Columnaris

Cause Desc: DIck Rupdolhs wife called???  She said their were about 40 dead crappie and bluegill in the Big, Wind and Church Pine lake chain along her shore.
Fish Kill Comment: Suspect columnaris, water temp mid-upper 60's panfish spawning period, other lakes have similair conditions.  I told her to call back if other fish started showing up and/or problem got worse over time.  Told her things should clear up in 10 -14 days.  She said thanks.

Cause Desc: water temps 68 degrees.  Large number of dead panfish reported by anglers and public.  No other fish species dead or observed.
Fish Kill Comment: Columnaris
Numerous calls received in both Barron and Spooner offices re fish kills.  Sent info/release to lake association (Bob Boyd) for distribution.  Primarily panfish and bass.

Panfish mainly bluegill and crappie reported by several citizens. No other fish seen or observed in large numbers by callers.  Given the time of the year and other columanirs outbreak in the area, attribute kill to columnaris.

Cause Desc: Low water levels lead to poor winter DO levels in this shallow lake.  Largemouth bass and panfish mainly impacted.
Recommended Action Desc: Resurveyd lake to determine if additional stocking is warranted.

Live Fish Desc: Fish dead for a couple of days.
Cause Desc: Heavy rain and ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION Friday 6/21/2013.  Water temperature 72-74 6/23/2013.  Post spawn for bluegill.  Conditions ideal for Columnaris outbreak.  Half dozen phones calls starting Monday.  Kill occurred on the weekend following the storm.
Fish Kill Comment: Estimate 500-1,000 dead fish on windy north shore.  Majority large bluegill and a few perch, bass and white bass.

Cause Desc: Columnaris

Live Fish Desc: Fresh dead some swimming in circles under the ice.  Angler report bite marks on some fish. Perhaps these are lisions.
Cause Desc: unknown but other fish kill occuring in the area.  Maybe oxygen super saturation or cold weather virus.
Activity Desc: Calm cold  good clear ice formation.  Sunny no snow to later.  Excellent conditions for oxygen production and accumulation.
Recommended Action Desc: Check DO levels collect fish if possible.
Fish Kill Comment: Two phone calls received by angers (David Hale 715-781-5973 and Jim Bennet, talked to brother Dick 715-386-5982) Tueday afternoon (Dec 3, 2013) noting dead and dying panfish ( almost all bluegill, one crappie noted, estimated by angler to be 1,000 dead fish throughout the bay) under the ice on Wednesday through Friday Nov. 27-29.  Kill appeared confined to Cedar Lake Bay in SW end of lake.  No dead fish reported outside of the bay.  Some walleye and northern being caught in the bay.

Live Fish Desc: One dead pike observed.  Panfish gulping for air near surface.
Cause Desc: Recent heavy rains caused lake to raise 7 feet over the past month.  On site investigation revealed surface DO's at 1ppm.   Water looked like dark coffee but did not smell.
Fish Kill Comment: Water resembled dark coffee.  Their is a large bog complex to the NE of this lake with two tribs that drain into the lake.  Its suspected the recent rains sent a slug of organic material from the bog complex into the lake causing photosynthesis to crash and causing DO levels to drop to 1 ppm or lower.  Recomneded concernd landowner put out winter aeration system to try and improve DO levels.

Cause Desc: Damman reported message on his voicemail that dead fish were present in Horse Lake Polk Co.  Caller was unsure how to id fish, so they did not know what they were.  Benike believes it is likely panfish, however will try and swing by Horse Lake this week to confirm.  Numerous columnaris infections going on right know in Polk County.
Fish Kill Comment: Technicians Stanley and Marsh drove by Horse Lake today in route to field work.  They report seeing a dozen or two black crappie on the south end of the lake and none by the public boat landing. Fish were rotten.  Been their for some time.  Attribute to columnaris.  No other fish seen or observed dead.

Cause Desc: Caller reported dead bluegill, PSD and crappie over the weekend.  Multiple columnaris kills going on locally at this time.  This lake is deeper and warms up slower than shallow lakes which pretty much are over at this time.
Fish Kill Comment: Columnaris, typical for this time of the year in the local area.  Told caller to call back if other fish like pike, walleye, suckers or minnows show up in large #'s.

Cause Desc: Columaris, Bluegill, Black Crappie
Winter DO Depletion.  DO testing in late winter indicated that DO levels were just above 1 ppm even though lake has an aeration system operating.
Fish Kill Comment: DO Depletion during winter if 2007-2008.  Early ice in combination with deep snow pack and late ice-out.  No dead fish were observed near the aeration hole during the winter of 2007-2008, however residents reported dead fish near the inlet of Lotus Lake in early April.  During ice-off of 2008, dead carp, bass and panfish were observed.  Electrofishing survey on 5-21-08 indicated that juvenile bluegill, black crappie and yellow perch were still present.  Only a handful of gamefish were captured, 2 largemouth bass and 3 northern pike.  Restock lake with top predators.  Panfish appear to be present in modest numbers.

Cause Desc: Caller reported lots of deadpanfish near Culvert by Osceola Rod and Gun Club.  Benike investigated on 6-19-09.  99% black crappie and 1 bluegill observed.  Kill effected probably 1000-1500 crappies.  No other dead fish observed or other dead aquatic life dead.  Fish kill was near culvert only, I walked the main lake shore and no dead fish were seen.  Their were also some live crappie which appeared stressed in and around the dead fish near the culvert.  They were off colored and were gasping for air.  Tried to grab one, but they were too stealthy.  Dead fish were too rotten to determine if Columnaris was likely the cause.  No noticeable tire tracks or  foul odor (other than dead fish) was present.  Considering only crappie appear effected and no other aquatic fish were dead, attribute kill to columnaris or possible DO depeltion from recent rainfall event the night before.
Fish Kill Comment: Columnaris, possible low DO from recent rain event.

Cause Desc: Water temp mid 60's.  Dead panfish reported.  No other dead fish seen or observed by public.

Fish Kill Comment: From warden Richter: I received a call from Bob Swan on August 11, 2012 at about 9:54 AM with a report of a fish kill on Mud Lake near Milton.  He said there were numerous crappie, shiners, and bluegills dead on the south shoreline of the lake.  I was in Albany when the call was received and had plans to meet Deputy Warden Kevin Christorf at the JSC at 11:00 AM.  After we met, we went to Mud Lake.  We found at least 100 crappie in the 11-12.5 inch range, numerous small bluegill, hundreds of shiners, one 15 inch largemouth bass, six perch, and several pumpkinseed dead along the south and southeast shoreline.  The color of the water was green and murky.  We then drove around and checked Clear Lake and another small lake connected to the DNR land to the northwest.  No additional dead fish were observed on these lakes and the water on these lakes did not appear to have as much algae in it.  We drove into the Blackhawk Campground and talked with someone fishing on Clear Lake.  The fisherman was catching healthy looking fish and did not see any dead ones.  We then drove to an access point to Mud Lake and talked with three fishermen that reported catching healthy bullheads, but noticed numerous dead crappies on the shoreline.  I noted there were numerous live turtles and frogs in and on the pond as well as seagulls and blue herons feeding on the dead fish. On August 12th, I called and left Bob Swan a voice mail message with a report of the D.O. level found on Mud Lake and said the likely cause of the fish kill was the fluctuation of the oxygen level after the rainfall last week.

Cause Desc: No dead fish observed yet, but a fishkill probably has occurred based on the following observations and measurements.   Attached are the dissolved oxygen and temperature profiles that Gavin King, our Lake Aeration Technician, recorded at two locations in Bucks Lake on January 16, 2007.  The very low dissolved oxygen concentrations from surface to bottom at this early point in winter along with the sulfur odor that you and Gavin noticed both indicate to me that there is strong likelihood that a winterkill of fish has already occurred in Bucks Lake this year.  Your suggestion about the possible cause of oxygen depletion is plausible.  Decomposition of the wetland vegetation recently flooded with the 1_ feet added to the dam in the 2007 renovation could increase the biological demand for oxygen beneath the ice.  The slight increase in oxygen concentration near the bottom is probably really hydrogen sulfide and not dissolved oxygen.  The temperature readings greater than 4¡ C  near the bottom probably reflect heat generated from anaerobic decomposition.  In my opinion, at this point emergency lake aeration to avoid a fishkill would not be worthwhile, and it could be counterproductive.  Circulating hydrogen sulfide throughout the water column may increase the chemical oxygen demand to consume the remaining oxygen where fish and other aquatic life might find refuge.  It's impossible to predict the severity of the winterkill from oxygen readings, but I would expect a behavioral response from several adaptive species that might find better conditions upstream in Hemlock Creek.  We'll try to visit Bucks Lake shortly after ice-out this spring to see if there's any evidence of a fishkill, and if so, to gauge the extent of losses.  Fortunately, as you observed after the last winterkill on Bucks Lake about 15 years ago, we should again expect a fast recovery for the fish community in this highly productive system.
Activity Desc: Dam renovations completed in fall 2007 increased reservoir elevation by about 1.5 feet and flooded wetland vegetation that's decomposing under the ice and consuming oxygen.
Recommended Action Desc:
Rusk County asked for information to investigate options for lake aeration and I provided the following to Gary Albrecht.    I talked with Greg Rublee about options for lake aeration at Bucks Lake, assuming that no electrical power is available nearby.  In our opinion, solar-powered systems are expensive ($8,000 to $10,000 for materials alone).  They have high maintenance needs (must remove snow from solar panels each time it snows).  Operation relies on sunlight (often scarce in winter) and battery storage.  Batteries have a limited lifetime and replacement and disposal are expensive.  Solar power aerators can only run small blowers so the open-water holes are pretty small too (maybe 20 x 20 feet), and the holes freeze again when the blowers stop.  Another lower-cost option that you might want to consider is a wind-powered aerator.  They don't rely on electricity, but instead they circulate water with a submerged propeller directly attached by a shaft to the wind vanes.  The units are installed on floats before ice-up and secured with lines to anchors on the lakebed.  The vanes are locked in place until ice is thick enough to put up a barricade.  Once the vanes are released, a hole opens pretty quickly.  Our Department has several wind aerators operating on lakes within the Chequamegon National Forest, including a heavy duty one (cost ~$4000, requires 5 mph wind speed) manufactured by LAS International at Lake Three in Ashland County west of Mellen, WI.  WDNR also has a much lighter and nicer one at Twin Lake in the far NE corner of Price County.  That unit was distributed by Keeton Industries www.keetonaquatics.com and sold for about $1200.  This one operated at lower wind speeds of 1 or 2 mph.  The last time we checked it was no longer in production, but Greg remembers them saying that if the demand was there, they might build more.  Greg will send you some photos by e-mail.  Wind-powered aerators also have some of the same limitations as solar aerator systems--small hole, dependent on wind, hole skims over, but usually opens again quickly.  But for the cost of one solar aerator, you could install several wind aerators, and their routine maintenance needs are far less too.
The log fetch and east-west orientation of Bucks Lake should be suitable to take advantage of prevailing west winds.  The location should be in the upstream third of the flowage, not down near the outlet.  Since the units are anchored to the lakebed, a permit would be necessary from Jon Kleist in our Water Regs and Zoning Section.  Another consideration is that winterkill of fish from oxygen depletion may not be a chronic problem at Bucks Lake.  I realize that there's interest in lake aeration now that we suspect a winterkill has occurred this season.  But as Paul suggested, that possible loss may be the result of greater biological oxygen demand from decomposing plant material from the wetlands that became flooded when the reservoir elevation increased last fall with the dam renovations.  It's hard to predict how often a similar event might happen in the future, but it also might be premature to take heroic measures right away.

Recommended Action Desc: No recommended action at this time.
Fish Kill Comment: This small fish kill comes 14 days after the lake was dyed blue with Aqua Blue by Aquatic Engineering at the behest of the Village of Lake Delton.  White suckers have been dying in small numbers all summer however.  It is not believed that this die-off came as a result of the dye job.  It is not likely that the die off was caused by low dissolved oxygen, high temperature, or any other sort of chemical agent.

Cause Desc: Average dissolved oxygen levels throughout the water column were very low (Figure 1). All DO measurement were below 0.8 mg/L in Long Lake and specific conductivity averaged 123 µS/cm. The mean temperature was 24.7 ¼C. Dissolved oxygen was 5.6 mg/L in a secondary channel of the Mississippi River immediately upstream of the outlet of Long Lake. In the Black River, near the Hwy. 35 bridge (station 8), DO was 5.4 mg/L. Duckweed covered nearly 100% of the NW side of the lake extending for a length of about 250m. Duckweed covered less than 50% of the remainder of the lake.  Flow patterns were visually estimated. Water entered the eastern entrance to the lake from Mud Lake (Big Marsh) and exited through Webb Slough to the south, and the outlet structure on the west into a secondary channel. Current velocities were substantial at the inflow station, and near both outflow station, and I attributed this to a recent extreme raise in the elevation of the Black River.  Based on these observations, its likely fish died from low dissolved oxygen attributable to high oxygen demand from water originating from Mud Lake. Mud Lake is highly eutrophic, and has very dense population of plants and is capable of consuming much of the oxygen input from Tank Creek, a secondary channel of the Black River. Previous fish kills, as late as three years ago, have also been linked to low oxygen levels.
Fish Kill Comment: About 200 total individuals of the following fish species were found on the surface in an advanced state of decay: spotted sucker, northern pike, crappie, redhorse species, yellow perch, bluegill and largemouth bass. Almost all fish were found in the large duckweed aggregation on the NW side of the lake, near the boat landing. Very few fish were seen in the open water found in most of the rest of the lake.
