Cause Desc: Powerline contractor punctured Blair to Whitehall sewer main.  Sewage ran off to Trempealeau River downstream of Lake Henry Dam in Blair, WI
Fish Kill Comment: Sewer pipe puncture occured @ 2:00 p.m. on 11/05/2013.  Fish crew investigation occured the following day @ 9:00 a.m.  No dead fish were observed directly below ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION point or at two road crossings downstream of ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION point.  Weather, river depth, and access issues prevented surveying river for live or dead fish.  Three sites downstream of ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION point were visited.  Water chemistry was measured with two YSI meters.  Dissolved Oxygen was > 9 ppm at all sites.  One site above ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION point was visited.  Dissolved oxygen was > 9 ppm.  City of Blair staff shut off AMPI (cheese factory) flow to sewer main date of puncture and ran radio and TV campaign to urge local residents to minimize water usage.  Both were effective at minimizing amount of sewage ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION to the river.  Cold water temperatures and water aeration from flow over Lake Henry dam (directly upstream of ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION point) also aided in minimizing impact to Trempealeau River.

Cause Desc: This morning Spooner desk got a call that there were dead lining the hatchery shore from Hyw 63 to the dam. I went and counted 162 bluegill, 7 largemouth, 6 black crappie 3 yellow perch and one pumpkinseed in that stretch of shoreline but there were many more along the hwy 63 causeway and the north shore of this basin of the Yellow river Flowage. The fish are in a fairly advanced state of decay to the point birds weren't eating them. It looked pretty much like a Columnaris kill when you get there a week or so after the fish died. I stopped a few places above hwy 63 and didn't find any more dead fish but I did find about a dozen dead bluegills at the Spooner lake dam. I had checked that area for winter kill mortality several weeks ago and had found nothing and we didn't notice any winter kill on Spooner Lake when we netted for northern this spring. It would seem a little late for winterkill stuff to be popping up now. I could get some putrid carcasses to Madison tomorrow but you won't be around to look at them. The good news at least is if it was viral it should show up in the Spooner lake sample we took since some mortality occurred there too.

Live Fish Desc: Normal
Cause Desc: Here is a Big Muskego northern pike fish kill observation update from Saturday July 16th fish kill investigation performed by Steve Gospodarek and Ben Heussner.  We travelled for one hour at an estimated 10 miles per hour covering 10 linear miles and observing approximately 300 feet wide.  Fish were easily observed as they were bloated and floating on a calm day and could be seen from a distance.  July 16, 2011 Big Muskego Fish Kill Observations                          Units           Distance Traveled        52800        linear ft.           Width of path observed        300        linear ft.         Area Observed per mile        15840000        cubic ft.       Total Acreage Covered        364        acres           Total Big Muskego Acreage        2300        acres           % Surface Water (subtract 25% emergent veg.)        75%                Total Surface Water Acreage        1725                   Conversion factor of Acreage Observed        5                   Number of Northern Morts Observed         128                 Total Potential Fish Kill Estimate        607                   Pre-Fish Kill Population Estimate        8734                   % of Total Adult Population        7%                 Based on our 2008 Big Muskego comprehensive report, the annual total mortality rate is 49% starting at age 3, which is a combination of natural, angling and hooking mortality.  The 7% estimated mortality of 607 fish is a maximum estimate as very few fish were observed throughout the majority of the lake, and dead northern pike were mainly observed at the south end or leeward side of the lake with recent north winds.  I would expect the 7% would not be additive to the total average annual mortality rate and most likely be insignificant when considering the added protection from angler harvest via the new restrictive 40 inch minimum length limit.  No fresh mortalities were observed, and no fish were collected for in depth fish health examination.  Early reports of stress were reported by anglers as northern had redness and irritation on the skin. The cause of the fish kill is likely due to a combination of factors including the following;Lower water levels resulting in lower carrying capacity of the lake's predator density.  Lower water levels causing higher average water temperatures in the high 80's and even in low 90's as reported by anglers.  High angling pressure combined with high water temperatures causing increased hooking mortality from catch and release.  The majority of the lake is looking good with a diversity of macrophytes covering the lake and water clarity is getting better.   We will continue to monitor the situation and continue to report results.  Data will be entered into the fish kill data base.
Fish Kill Comment:
currently in a drawdown 6" below normal levels, higher water temperatures in the high 80's.

Most likely  a combination of high water temps, hooking mortality and reduced carrying capacity of the lake.

Primary Land Use: The upland watershed is comprised of urbanization combined with agriculture.  Riparian land use is primarily wetlands followed by agriculture and some dwellings in upland areas.
Live Fish Desc: Many panfish and bass were observed with no health concerns.  The only northern pike observed were already a day or two post mortem.  Angler reports have been good despite hot weather indicating an overall healthy fishery.
Cause Desc: Sue Marquenski noted on July 9,2012:  Extremely hot weather resulting in sustained high water temps could be the ultimate cause of death; also in combination with stress associated bacterial infections such as Aeromonas hydrophila, and if algae are dying, low DO and possible algal toxin release.  If algae are not dying, O2 supersaturation could also be a factor.  I checked BeckerÀs Fishes of WI and experimentally, n pike have been acclimated to temps as high as 89.6-95.5 ; Eaton et al. 1995  (attached) determined that the max temp for n pike is 83-86 F if sustained for a week.  About 5-10 (?) years ago we had reports of n pike dying in the Yahara River during another heat wave, so they do not tolerate extreme temps and if a cooler refugium is not available, they can die just from physiological changes caused by extreme temps (critical cellular reactions just do not happen at certain temps for certain species of fish).  If a fish has been trying to cope with extreme temps for several days, changes occur in the kidney that we can see histologically if the fish is either alive (weak, moribund) at collection, euthanized, bagged and put on ice and necropsied within 12 hours.  If fish in this condition are not available, we cannot tell by exam if the cause of death was temperature related.  We can still examine moribund  fish or freshly dead fish if the gills are at least pink to red, for pathogens.
Activity Desc: Angling, boating.  No major construction or ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION potential.
Recommended Action Desc: Supplemental northern pike stocking to boost recruitment and contribute to biomanipulation efforts.   Temporary fishing  closures during extended warm weather periods.
Fish Kill Comment: Northern pike are the primary fish species affected, although a few bluegills, bullheads and one bass were also observed.  Sustained high water temperatures are definitely the major cause.   Angling pressure is always high on this waterbody, and catch and release may be a contributing factor.   A similar fish kill was observed during low water periods last year at this time.

Live Fish Desc: Dead fish at different stages of decomposition at ice off. No live or moribund fish present. Gizzard shad was the only species affected. Entire lake was affected.
Cause Desc: Normal winter die off of gizzard shad. Adult die offs of this species are common. Normally it happens under the ice and the fish are decomposed by ice off. This year's early ice out meant the mortality was more noticeable than normal.
Activity Desc: Normal winter ice over with early ice off

Live Fish Desc: Bullheads on the surface were gulping air.  Numerous small shiners and suckers were dead around the shoreline
Cause Desc: Heavy rains caused liquid manure spread on an ag field to runoff into a mapped intermittent stream and into a neighbor's private pond causing BOD to increase and DO to plummet.
Recommended Action Desc: None.  À        Manure spread from Circle H Dairy owned by David and Gary Hass does not appear to have been overapplied or applied in violation of NRCS standard 590.  There were no setback or incorporation requirements for the field on which they applied.  As listed in NRCS standard 590 Considerations section: ÀConsider delaying surface applications of manure or other organic byproducts if precipitation capable of producing ANTHROPOGENIC CONDITION forecast within 24 hours of the time of planned application.À  Although not a requirement, in this situation, the manure surface application should have been delayed due to forecasted rain.  The Department recommended the pond owner aerate the pond as much as possible.

Primary Land Use: Glatz Creek (aka Buckstaff Creek) flows primarily through open and ag land in its upper reaches and urban in its lower half.
Live Fish Desc: At the time of the phone call and visits there were 1000's of 4 - 6 inch gizzard shad holding just above the mouth of the creek mouth to Lake Winnebago.  There were very few dead fish at this time.  Most all shad looked in good shape with no abnormal swimming behavior
Cause Desc: Falling water temps cause the shad, which are at the edge of their range, crowd into these areas.
Fish Kill Comment: This is a fairly common situation on the Winnebago system at this time of year. In central Wisconsin we are at the northern limits of the gizzard shad's range.  Seasonally as winter approachs, we see YOY's or yearlings pack into creek mouths and discharge areas by the 1000's looking for warmer water.  They are a fragile fish and frequently die by the thousands.

Live Fish Desc: Only one live fish was seen, a northern pike that was slowly swimming along the surface.  All other fish observed appeared dead for 24 - 48 hours.
Cause Desc: Environmental conditions for 2 weeks prior to the reported kill were clear, calm and very hot; 90's and even very low 100's.  Surface water temps in many shallow areas were pushed into the upper 80's and low 90's.
Fish Kill Comment: Kill was exclusively northern pike.  From Boom Bay to the mouth of the Wolf River at Poygan, up the river to Fremont and around the perimeter of Partridge Lake 276 adult northern pike were counted.  Fish appeared to have been dead 24 - 48 hours.  No fish were measured but visual observation was that they ranged in size from 22 - 40+ inches, with an average size of about 30".  Only other dead fish were 4 dead carp that were likely from a recent carp die-off likely due to the  high water temperatures combined with spawning stress.
